{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bd48099d-6515-4857-b546-547d82a28abb","content":"This repo doesn't contain documentation on that topic, but here's the general guidance:\n\n## Recovering a macOS crash dump without `createdump`\n\nNativeAOT apps don't ship `createdump`. On macOS you rely on the OS-level crash reporting:\n\n1. **Check for Apple crash logs** — macOS automatically writes crash reports to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for `.ips` or `.crash` files matching your process name.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** before running:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Core files are written to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n3. **Disable SIP restrictions** (if needed) — System Integrity Protection can suppress core dumps for some paths. On dev machines you may need to adjust this via `csrutil`.\n\n4. **Analyze the dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n5. **For richer .NET diagnostics**, set the environment variable:\n   ```bash\n   export DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\n   export DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4   # Full heap dump\n   ```\n   Though with NativeAOT these may have limited effect compared to CoreCLR.\n\nThe Apple crash log (step 1) is usually the easiest starting point since it requires no prior setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"df2dc97f-9f64-432b-8a2c-c85e3c662d61","outputTokens":352,"requestId":"784F:3038F3:1FE0969:235A5B6:69FA9E7C"},"id":"487e1974-7814-4cf5-ad05-c7b317ebe988","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:51:02.369Z","parentId":"9b9dcaca-0c8a-4f91-9457-5d06bc6432d8"}
